label: University of Pennsylvania Ms. Codex 747: Aurora
attribution: Provided by the University of Pennsylvania Libraries
description:
Summary: Verse paraphrase of the Bible: Old Testament (excluding Psalms, prophets and some other books) (f. 1-109v); New Testament (Gospels and Acts, excluding Epistles and Revelation) (f. 109v-149v).
        Language: Latin
        Support: parchment
        Extent: 
        Collation: 
        Layout: Written in 60 long lines; ruled in lead; some prickings visible.
        Script: Written in a Gothic book script by a single hand, with marginal commentary in a second hand.
        Decoration: Red and blue used for initials; rubricated headings throughout; diagram or chart of the deadly sins (f. 50r); faint sketch of the Virgin[?] (f. 125).
        Binding: Modern half leather over wooden boards with old guards (2 vellum incunable leaves from a canonical text with commentary, probably printed by Peter SchoÌˆffer of Mainz).
        Origin: Written in France, mid-13th century (Zacour-Hirsch).
        Cite as:	
        UPenn Ms. Codex 747
        For catalog record, see Permanent Link: 2487568 http://hdl.library.upenn.edu/1017/d/medren/2487568
  For TEI description and digital images, see: http://openn.library.upenn.edu/Data/0002/html/mscodex747.html
